  "prompt": "Does it hurt to get stitches?",
  "response": "Getting stitches can cause some discomfort and pain, but the level of pain varies depending on several factors, such as the location of the wound, the severity of the injury, and the individual's pain tolerance. \n\nTypically, healthcare providers will administer a local anesthetic to numb the area before stitching, which helps minimize pain during the procedure. After the local anesthetic wears off, there might be some soreness or mild pain around the stitched area, which can be managed with over-the-counter pain relievers like acetaminophen or ibuprofen.\n\nIf you are concerned about pain or have specific questions about the procedure, it is best to discuss them with your healthcare provider. They can provide more personalized information and address any concerns you might have.",
